    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{3+\frac{1}{a}}}{{a+4}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{3a+1}{a\mathopen{}\left(a+4\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{3+\frac{1}{a}}}{{a+4}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{3+\frac{1}{a}}</m> and <m>{a+4}</m>, which is <m>{a}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{3+\frac{1}{a}}}{{a+4}} \amp = \frac{({3+\frac{1}{a}})\cdot{a}}{({a+4})\cdot{a}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{3a+1}}{{a\mathopen{}\left(a+4\right)}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Although <m>{a}</m> was canceled, <m>a \ne 0</m> is implied in the solution. There is no need to treat <m>a \ne 0</m> as a lost condition.</p>
</solution>
